segments.text: One, two, three, four, five, six.
Testing, testing.
One, two, three, four, five, six.
Testing.
Six, five, four, three, two, one.
Six, five, four, three, two, one.
Testing, testing.
This is testing, testing, testing, testing, testing.
Hello.
Testing here.
Okay.
This is September the 4th, I believe.
And we are in room 207 of the Evans Library, and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Dr. Paige Morgan, a longtime neighbor and friend, and today we're chatting about his...
experiences as an A&M former student.
Paige, to begin with, introduce yourself to anyone who might listen or read a transcript.
Describe family background, growing up, where'd you go to high school.
Just talk about yourself before you came to A&M.
So, my name is Paige Wesley Morgan.
I grew up in the area around Wichita Falls, Texas, although I was
born in Arizona.
My mother was a member of an old ranching family in northwest Texas and I went to high school in Iowa Park.
It was a small place but had a fairly progressive high school.
I got to take algebra and trigonometry and
uh, chemistry and some things like that in high school.
So that was all very positive.
And, uh, early on then, I guess I was influenced by being in the 4-H club and, and, uh, my 4-H club leader, uh, county assistant, a county, county agent.
brought me down to A&M several times for the 4-H club roundup, convinced me that I needed to go to A&M, and that's sort of how it all got started then.
So you had been to visit.
What impression did A&M make on you when you came to visit?
Well, being from a rather small place, although A&M was not very big at the time, it seemed big to me, and

I guess it had a reputation and an aura about it and its graduates and a loyalty that I saw in them and another thing that was in my family background was I'd had two uncles and two cousins come to A&M before I did none of them graduated none of them really got close to graduating so when I decided to come to A&M
The ones of those people that were still living all said, you know, you're our last hope for ever, a graduate from A&M.
So that was one of the things in my background.
And there was no fish camp in those days, was there?
No.
Was there anything before enrolling?
We came a week before the upperclassmen came.
And we had our freshman orientation.

I remember there were no parents stayed around for that you know I mean they all uh most of the parents didn't are we on most of the parents didn't even uh bring their children you know their sons they just they a lot of them hitchhiked here and road buses and train and everything and got here the best they could and

and I remember when that week was over the upperclassmen that were our uh our company officers told us that the upperclassmen are coming in this weekend if you got any good judgment at all you'll get out of here and not come back until the very last minute on Sunday night so that was what we all did we all hadn't planned to leave but we were all pretty encouraged where did you go
My roommate and I were both from Iowa Park and we hitchhiked home and hitchhiked back and got here in the middle of the night on Sunday night.
Started our first year.
Now when you came at the beginning of that week, how did you get down here?
Did mom and dad bring you or a relative?
His mother brought us.
Okay.
My mother was a school teacher and she'd already started to work I guess that
so she couldn't get off.
I guess my dad was not as impressed with this whole activity as she was.
Did you get any advice from anybody, parents or anybody else, before you left?
Did they tell you anything to do or not do?
Do you remember?
I can't remember that.
I remember that my roommate's mother
who was a widow, was a little, you know, emotional when she left us down here, but other than that, I don't remember really.
It seems like one of my uncles told me that he expected me to, you know, represent the family well or something like that, and that was about it.
Did, what did you think you were going to do in terms of major and

long time future when you at that point at that point in my life that uncle that i just mentioned was one of the dominant male figures and he was a successful rancher and i kind of envisioned myself as becoming a junior partner and getting my mother had a part of the family estate and you know i sort of thought that i would move into the ranching business by that

means and but other than that the other thing that was in my head was could I make it you know could I go to what by our standards was a major college and graduate so being from a small high school not having much how many in senior class about 42 42
And I presume you were like I, that you had not traveled much around the region.
Well, not in academic circles at all.
My father's father lived in California when I was in high school, when I was in school, grade school and high school.
And we'd gone out there a couple of times.
So that was my extent of traveling was
two or three trips to California.
Do you remember what you brought with you when you came to enroll?
What, how much stuff?
I guess I had a small suitcase and a foot locker,

and I remember I had a radio and maybe one change of civilian clothes they told us to take not bring anything else that we couldn't wear it anyway and so Now this was the fall of 19 51 51 and when your when your roommate's mother drove away
Y'all were then in the hands of what, seniors or sophomores?
Juniors and seniors.
Juniors and seniors.
This was a time that the Corps had just come back maybe a year or two before, maybe just that year, from Bryan Air Force Base.
And so we were still in outfits that had cadre of upperclassmen and then we were all freshmen.
And there were no sophomores in those units until either after Christmas or sometime in the middle of the spring semester we finally got two or three sophomores.
Do you have any idea how you got assigned to your outfit?
What was it?
What was that outfit like?
I can't remember for sure.
I think we had some choice of which unit that we would be in.
And I don't, it seems to me like that that county agent whose name was Bill Pallmeyer and who called me just a few days ago, he's still alive, still, you know, interested in my wife and I.
By the way, she was in the 4-H club, too, so he knew her and I both.
I think he was in the Transportation Corps, so I think I may have chosen that because of him.
Now, what outfit was it?
Well, it was just A Transportation Corps.
I don't think the unit exists anymore.
So it didn't have a letter or a G-1 or H-5?
No, it was A.
Then...

in a battalion it was Company A and there was B, C, and D but they were not the Transportation Corps they were other well I guess there was at the my freshman year there may have been two well I'm not sure I don't know.
And you were assigned to dorm space where?
The dorm right across the street from the
uh, exchange store, the, uh, uh, beside, uh, G.F. Gondblank.
That's not, that's not the Zell, is it?
No, no, it was over by the, uh, Sabisa.
Yeah, yeah.
Uh, I, what was the name of that?
We'll think about that later.
I've forgotten that.
Uh, describe how the upperclassmen whipped you fish into shape.
How did they get y'all
began to break you in and orient you?
Well, they, the people that were our officers in our units were pretty benevolent, kind-hearted types.
They picked them, I think, for that.
They were trying to

prepare us to learn everything that we needed to learn and to adopt the sort of mind state that we had to go through this so this was sort of the way I guess the way we viewed it was that we were sort of running a long gauntlet that was going to be a year long you know and we were going to be beset by all sorts of challenges from every direction and
we were sort of preparing ourselves to survive.
But I remember the first week we were here, we were marching everywhere we would go for some sort of an orientation meeting or something.
We were marching.
They marched us down Military Walk from in front of Sevesa there, and we went by Walton Hall, which was the dorm that the athletes were in in those days.
And I guess we were going to Gine Hall for some kind of a meeting.
And so all these very irreverent athletes were hanging out the windows there on Walton.
Was it Walton?
Anyway, they were yelling at us, you know, your mommies are, you know, you go home to mommies, you know, and you'll never,
None of you will be here in six weeks.
And look around.
Everybody that you can see will have quit before Christmas and everything.
And unfortunately, a lot of what they were saying was true.
There was a big dropout during the first year that I was here.
And during those first few days, was there much hazing and so forth that went on?
No, not really.
I don't remember.
They taught us how to whip out or introduce ourselves and things like that, and they said, now I'm going to imitate what a sophomore is going to do to you, you know, and that sort of thing.
It was not, I don't remember that as being particularly terrifying, but the first sophomore I met, I remember that was particularly terrifying.
Describe that.

Well, you know, we were, it could have been that first Sunday night or maybe the first Monday night after school started and we had to go someplace and come back and we were stopped out in front of the dorm and stood out there at attention for what seemed like a year, probably was 15 minutes, you know, and people walking around us describing how
poorly we were dressed and how our shoeshines were inadequate and everything, you know.
Now, did you go through academic registration?
They had registration in those days, but there was, this was just after the Korean War had started.
And so my class was a record-sized class.
I'm sure there were a lot of people who decided to go to A&M that were hoping to stay out of the war.
And so when we went through registration, it was at the end of that week of orientation.
It was before the upperclassmen had gotten back.
And they had pre-assigned us, depending on which major we chose,

and I guess in my case it had to do with whether or not I'd had trigonometry and plane geometry and chemistry those were the three deciding courses I believe and since I had well they put us all of the people that were majoring in wildlife science and range management and a couple of other majors all in the same block of sections so we just got a you know an assignment of came straight out of the catalog
Do you remember what your major title was then?
Were you, was it just agriculture or was it more specific for you?
Well, during that week of orientation, I was wavering back and forth between some sort of engineering and something to do with agriculture.
And I finally decided to major in,

range management because of the family connection to the ranching industry so I actually chose range management as a freshman and stayed with that all the way through my four years it was called ranging the department and the degree were called range and forestry and Stephen F. Austin had the only accredited forestry program in the state at the time and A&M
wanted it I guess and so they had this degree called a range in forestry and I think we took maybe two forestry courses had one person that taught in that area.
Do you have any idea what your academic load was that first semester?
15, 18 hours?
No, it was 19 hours.
Uh-huh.
And describe your impression, your first impression of those courses and the instructors.
Well, I guess I was very concerned to start out with that, you know, everything was going to be extremely difficult and

and I did have a hard time with English I remember I didn't do particularly well in English but right off the bat I began to take quizzes and do fairly well and I found out that a lot of people around me in my outfit and others that were in that section were not doing so well and so I began to realize that you know that

that not only could I survive but I could actually do you know above average academically and that was a great relief to me you know when the first grades came out and I well they had exemptions in those days so I was exempted from all of my finals I think except one or something like that and then I made you know a distinguished student uh
GPA at the end of that semester.
So that began to kind of build up my confidence.
Did you have some instructors and or courses that first semester that you now realize were significant to you later in the impression they made on you?

I've thought about that some since I scheduled to do this and I'm not sure now whether they were the first semester or the second semester but I had a biology course with Mr. Dobson who or Dr. Dobson and he made a really good impression on me and

I remember one time he asked me after must have been the second semester because he asked me what my GPA was and I was apparently a little having a little ego problem at the time you know so I told him and I know that I was feeling really proud and he said oh Paige you can do better than that so
Then, you know, that made me think, well, you know he's right.
I could do better than that.
So he was one of the people that had students over for dinner occasionally.
And that was a big milestone in my life, you know, was to actually
visit with the professor on a social level rather than just to see him in the classroom, to meet his family, to meet his kids and everything.
That made a big impression on me.
And, uh, were there, what about English or math or science?
Well, uh, the, uh, I don't

I remember some of the English professors I've looked back at the math I can't identify who I had as a math instructor but I had Mr. Hedgecock and Greer and Shepherd I remember in English and all of them were probably pretty tolerant of

semi-literate West Texas kids you know and I probably learned a lot about writing in those under those people even though I didn't you know make I can't remember I must have made a B in one under one of them but anyway I remember them I remember Victor Whining was in the English department
And I had been a debater in high school.
And so I got on the debate team here at A&M and did that for a couple of years.
And that was a real enlightening experience.
And all of those faculty members were full-time faculty.
No such thing then as what we today call TAs.
No.
No, they were all.
And about how large were the sections in number of students?
Any big ones?
Chemistry was really big.
I remember that.
Like over a hundred, I guess.
It was in the big lecture room in the chemistry building.
I don't remember any other big sections.
40 or 50 students was probably the largest of anything.
And did you feel that the faculty members were accessible if you wanted to talk to them?
Well, I guess I did, but I didn't really ever do that very much.
Some of the faculty, I remember one of the English professors insisted that we make appointments and come by and talk to him.
And that was good for a young kid from a small town.
But the faculty didn't act aloof or distant or anything like that.

you know they all seem to be very human approachable people uh the in in terms of academics then you didn't come close to flunking anything you were doing well did you feel begin to feel that your high school had prepared you pretty well yes i did and i remember one time thinking that oh i i

after a year or so I was invited to speak to a assembly back at my high school and I remember encouraging the kids to you know to take the hard courses in high school don't wait until you go to college to take trig and calculus or chemistry or biology or you know and and I remember that
that I had the impression that I didn't really communicate that very well.
Most of the kids weren't as serious about it as they should have been.
Now, meanwhile, describe what life was like in the dormitory, and what was a typical class day?
What time did y'all get up?
What happened when?
Begin at daylight and take me through 10, 30, 11 o'clock at night on typical class day.
Well, I'm not sure about actual times, but it, I imagine that we got up about 6 30, and we
had about 15 minutes from the time we got up until we were due in formation.

out in front of the dorm, and we would march into Sabisa and eat breakfast, and then we had a little time before classes, the first class of the day, and since we were carrying 18 or 19 hours, all of us, well, we had a, and in my section, everybody had two or three laps, so
We were busy most of the day going to classes and you came back to the dorm and you had a formation for lunch.

You marched into the building for lunch and of course we all sat together as a unit and there was assigned upperclassmen on each table and we learned to give meal service to the upperclassmen and not eat until we served them and

uh everything and um one thing that that you know that was interesting was we had a number of waiters in our unit and those were special guys you know they were they were the poorest of the poor I guess you know they were working their way through A&M and and so they would had to get up earlier than we did and everything but I remember a lot of those guys were
really hard-working, serious kids, you know.
Did they also kind of help your outfit, maybe get a little extra serving every now and then?
The freshmen were all encouraged to stay in the dining hall until they had eaten as much as they wanted, you know, so the last people to leave every meal were always the freshmen.
and our waiter friends would be sure that there was plenty of stuff left on our table when the upperclassmen left.
Now how did you and your buddies learn all of the vocabulary for the food and everything?
the nicknames, were you taught that?

We were taught that mostly during that week of orientation and it's amazing how fast you can learn if you're under the threat you know nothing bad ever really happened to anyone but it just seemed like if somebody was yelling at you you could learn faster than if you just could either do it or not do it
Did you have enough time to actually to eat?
Yes, yes.
Mainly because there were only one or two upperclassmen per table.
And it was, you know, at the time, I guess it seemed fairly traumatic.
But looking back on it, it was fairly amusing, you know, to some of the things that happened and everything.
It wasn't that bad.
Were there any foods that you remember that were new to you?

They had combinations of things uh well I guess I had never eaten uh trying to remember they they had tamales they had a Mexican meal that had tamales in it and beans and rice and I've forgotten what else you know I don't think I'd ever had
many tamales in my whole life you know maybe at least that wasn't a major thing that we ate and uh they had cream puffs but the freshmen rarely ever got to eat cream puffs so.
Were there kush questions in your outfit?
Yes.
Do you remember some of your pet kush questions?
Well there were certain kinds of cush questions for which there was no acceptable correct answer Such as?

How many tiles are there in the bottom of the swimming pool and even if you went over and counted them you were not going to win that cush question you know you were gonna that was the kind of question they asked when the upperclassmen wanted your dessert so that but that was okay
Was there any, say on desserts, was there any dessert that was kind of everybody's favorite that y'all really looked forward to?
Well, I think cream puffs fit into that category because the upperclassmen always ask difficult questions.
When they had cream puffs and the freshmen,
I don't know whether we really liked them or not.
It was just that we thought that they were good because we couldn't get one.
And what were the least favorite foods?
Or were there any?
Well, I remember they served stewed tomatoes with bread, and there were usually a lot of that left.
I can't, I can't remember what else.
Now when you went home, either Thanksgiving, Christmas, or Easter, did you, like I've heard a few others, forget and use some of the Aggie lingo at the table at home and almost get in trouble?
I, I don't remember doing that, but I remember that, you know, people talking about doing it, and some of the
Some of the nomenclature was pretty crude, and I could visualize getting in trouble if you used some of that.
Now, as your routine of study began to take shape, if you had any free time during the day, where did you go to spend that time, whether to study or to just relax?
Where did you go?
Well, I mostly went back to my room because we didn't have many upperclassmen in our dorm and uh, uh, the, the dorm was not a, you know, not a stressful place to be during the day.
And uh, I don't remember hanging out at, well, one thing about it was that if you were in your dorm, our dorms were off limits to sophomores and that was one of the,
few places on campus that you couldn't become the source of amusement for two.
